ted for letters like 1 for I and 0 for O, special characters are getting corrupted, and some letters are just disappearing entirely. Looking at examples like \"BEEF STEW W1TH R00T VEGETABLES\" and \"ŁAZANK1 ZE ŚM1ĘTANQ\", it's clear the OCR engine is struggling with both regular text and especially with Polish diacritical marks. I'm noticing a pattern where some items are picking up section headers instead of their actual titles. Looking at the cases where this happens—like Braised Fennel with Tomato grabbing \"VEGETABLE SIDES\" and Herb Crusted Cod getting \"SEAFOOD MAINS\"—it seems the algorithm is sometimes latching onto the wrong line entirely. But for Zupa Brukułowa, it actually did find the correct title line, just with OCR errors mangling the characters. So I need to distinguish between cases where the wrong section is being extracted versus cases where the right line is just garbled. Looking at these extraction errors, I'm seeing a pattern where the extractor sometimes grabs variant titles or section headers instead of the main recipe title. With the Żurawina Kompot example, it picked the second variant when the first part should be canonical, and for Zupa Jarzynowa z Kluskami, it pulled a section header entirely. Now I'm noticing cases where it's pulling content from the middle or end of the recipe instead of the actual title line. I'm noticing a pattern where the extraction is pulling metadata and section headers instead of actual recipe titles—things like servings info, notes headers, and category tags. There's also a case sensitivity issue with \"Minestrone Soup\" where the all-caps version is technically correct but doesn't match the expected format, and some entries are grabbing intermediate section labels like \"GLAZE:\" instead of the recipe name itself. I see the pattern now—some of these \"failures\" have the extracted text matching the expected output exactly, which suggests the issue isn't with extraction accuracy but rather with how the titles are positioned in the input. For cases like Strawberry Shortcake, the actual recipe title isn't appearing in the first few lines where my extraction logic is looking, so even though the expected value exists somewhere in the document, it's not being found by the current approach. lines shown. Yet it was extracted correctly. But still fails.\n   - Vanilla Panna Cotta - first line IS \"Vanilla Panna Cotta\". Yet extracted matches expected but still fails.\n\n   Hmm, maybe the \"failure\" here is that the extracted title LOOKS right but there's a subtle difference not visible in the digest? Like trailing whitespace, unicode normalization, etc.?\n\n   Or wait - maybe the digest is showing a simplified display and the actual extracted value has some artifact?\n\n   Actually for Karp Pieczony: Expected \"Karp Pieczony\", Extracted \"Roasted Carp with Almond & Raisin Sauce\" - the first line IS \"Karp Pieczony\" but the extractor picked line 2. So the extractor chose the subtitle/translation over the actual title.\n\n   For Barszcz Ukraiński, the title's split across two lines with \"BARSZCZ\" on the first and \"UKRAIŃSKI\" on the second, but only the second line got extracted. And with Oscypek Smażony, the extractor somehow grabbed \"SERVING SUGGESTIONS:\" instead of the actual title on the first line. There's a pattern here where the extractor is picking secondary content or partial lines instead of the primary title.\n\n   Let me look at what's actually happening with the extraction logic. The issue seems to be that when titles span multiple lines or when there are subtitles present, the extractor isn't reliably grabbing the right one. I need to understand the extraction method better to see where it's going wrong.\n\nI'm seeing a pattern where the extractor is pulling secondary content—subtitles, translations, or lines from elsewhere in the recipe—instead of the actual primary title. For Oscypek Smażony specifically, it grabbed \"SERVING SUGGESTIONS:\" which appears at the end of the recipe entirely. This suggests the extraction logic might be searching for content in the wrong location or prioritizing the wrong elements. I need to examine the extraction method more closely to understand why it's skipping over the actual titles on the first lines. I'm seeing more OCR substitution errors like the currency symbol being read as E, and now I'm noticing a third pattern where compound titles are being extracted incorrectly—sometimes pulling the full \"A : B\" format when only the first part is needed, or grabbing the second variant instead. There's also a fourth pattern emerging where the extractor is pulling content from completely wrong sections of the recipe, like jumping to serving suggestions instead of staying near the actual title. I'm noticing some recipes where the extraction algorithm picked up metadata or formatting artifacts instead of the actual title. With Chleb Żytni, it grabbed the servings line, and Kompot Porzeczkowy got a notes section. Lentil Vegetable Soup has a category tag mixed in, and Minestrone Soup is being extracted in all caps when it should be title case—the algorithm is matching the formatting from the source rather than normalizing it properly. Looking at the actual file structure for these recipes, the title appears consistently on line 5 after metadata lines. For Sałatka ze Świeżych Warzyw, the extractor pulled \"INSTRUKCJE:\" from deep within the recipe instead of the correct title on line 5 - another instance of grabbing content from the wrong section. Same issue with Kompot Porzeczkowy where the title should be on line 5 but the extractor is returning something else entirely.\n\nNow examining Minestrone Soup, which has an unusual layout with decorative separators and the ingredients header appearing before the title. The extractor did find \"MINESTRONE SOUP\" correctly, but it's a case sensitivity problem - the expected format is \"Minestrone Soup\" with proper title casing.\n\nLooking at the other \"identical but failed\" cases like Kompot Malinowy and Strawberry Shortcake, these might be false positives caused by invisible Unicode characters or encoding artifacts in the digest display rather than actual failures. I need to recount the failures since the numbers seem inconsistent - the digest claims 40 failures but I'm seeing discrepancies between what's reported and what's actually listed. Continuing through the list, I'm at entries 15 through 31 now. Still counting to verify the total—we're getting closer to that 40 mark the user mentioned.\n\nLooking at the remaining items, I see entries 32 through 40, including some Polish dishes I initially missed like Żurawina Kompot and Żurek z Kielbasą. That brings me to the full count of 40 recipes. Now I need to organize these into clean groupings by category or section.\n\nI'm noticing a pattern where certain recipes have a category header with a page number as their title—like \"VEGETABLE SIDES 145\" for Braised Fennel with Tomato, or \"SEAFOOD MAINS 78\" for Herb Crusted Cod. There are seven of these cases so far. I'm starting to see another pattern emerging with OCR artifacts, but let me continue examining the structure. bling of correctly-identified title (10 cases)**\nThe extractor identified the right line but OCR substitutions make it fail exact matching:\n- Beef Stew with Root Vegetables → \"BEEF STEW W1TH R00T VEGETABLES\" (1/0 for I/O)\n- Beet and Walnut Salad → \"BEET ANO WALNUT SAL1A\" (character substitutions)\n- Łazanki ze Śmietaną → \"ŁAZANK1 ZE ŚM1ĘTANQ\"\n- Marinated Mushroom Salad → \"MAR1NATED MUSHROOM SALAD\"\n- Mushroom Crepe Appetizer → \"MUSHROOM CREPE APPET1ZER\"\n- Pan-Roasted Chicken with Thyme → \"PAN-R0ASTED CHICKEN WITH THYME\"\n- Roasted Garlic and Herb Salmon → \"ROASTED GARLIC ANO HERB SAL1WN\"\n- Zupa Brukułowa → \"Zupa Bru1<ó1owa\"\n- Zupa z Dyni i Imbiru → \"ZUPA Z DYN1 1 1MB1RU\"\n- Żurek z Kielbasą → \"ŻUR€K Z KI€LBASĄ\"\n\n**Pattern C: Content extracted from wrong position in recipe (10 cases)**\nThe extractor sometimes grabs text from elsewhere in the recipe instead of the title area—like pulling \"SERVING SUGGESTION:\" or other body content when the actual title is nearby.\n\n**Pattern D: Metadata/header lines before title selected (4 cases)**\nWhen recipes have multiple metadata lines in the layout, the extractor occasionally picks one of those header lines instead of the actual recipe title.\n\n**Pattern E: Case normalization issues (2-5 cases)**\nSome titles are being extracted correctly but aren't being converted from all-caps to proper title case.\n\n**Pattern F: Multi-line title - only partial captured (1 case)**\nWhen a title spans multiple lines, only the second line gets picked up instead of the full title.\n\n**Pattern G: Subtitle**\nI'm seeing cases where extracted text pulls from the wrong line entirely—like when an English translation appears below the Polish title and gets selected instead, or when section headers get captured rather than the actual dish name. Much of the compound gets extracted in one case while the other pulls too little. Looking at three more cases—Kompot Malinowy, Strawberry Shortcake, and Vanilla Panna Cotta—the extractions appear correct visually, though there could be hidden Unicode differences or trailing spaces causing the mismatch. Now I'm tallying up the patterns I've found: section headers with page numbers show up 7 times, OCR garbling appears in 10 cases, content from wrong positions in 10, metadata lines before titles in 3 specific recipes, and case normalization issues making up the rest.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":33780,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":33780},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"59e08a96-9770-4abb-9160-1e897202b2f